The robe is adorned with symbols such as {{ill|Swastika|ja|卍|12=draft}} (right-facing), the sun, thunder, clouds, rocks, and the moon, reflecting esoteric {{ill|Mikkyō|ja|密教|12=draft}} mandalas. These elements are attributed to the "One Body, Two Buddhas" doctrine of a sect of sculpting priests from the {{ill|Jōdo-shū|ja|浄土宗|12=draft}}, combining {{ill|Amida Nyorai|ja|阿弥陀如来|12=draft}} with {{ill|Vairocana|ja|大日如来|12=draft}}.<ref name=town/><ref name=":4" />
== Legend == A local legend recounts that during the construction of a large {{ill|torii|ja|鳥居|12=draft}} for Suwa Taisha in [[1657]] (Meireki 3), a stonecutter attempted to use the current stone Buddha as material. However, upon striking it with a chisel, the stone bled. Afraid of divine retribution, the construction ceased. The stone was later consecrated as an Amida Nyorai.<ref name=town/><ref name=kanko/>
