{{Infobox artwork | image_file = Yashiro, Shimosuwa, Suwa District, Nagano Prefecture 393-0000, Japan - panoramio.jpg | painting_alignment = right | image_size = 300px | title = Manji no Sekibutsu | caption = Front view | year = [[1660]] (Manji 3) | type = {{ill|Stone Buddha|ja|石仏|12=draft}} | material = {{ill|Andesite|ja|安山岩|12=draft}} (hornblende-pyroxene andesite) | height_metric = 2.6 | width_metric = 3.8 | metric_unit = m | accession = | city = {{ill|Shimosuwa, Nagano|ja|下諏訪町|12=draft}}, {{ill|Nagano Prefecture|ja|長野県|12=draft}} | museum = | website = {{URL|1=https://www.town.shimosuwa.lg.jp/www/contents/1001000000750/index.html|2=Manji no Sekibutsu (Shimosuwa Town)}} }}
'''Manji no Sekibutsu''' (万治の石仏) is a {{ill|stone Buddha statue|ja|石仏|12=draft}} located in {{ill|Shimosuwa|ja|下諏訪町|12=draft}}, {{ill|Nagano Prefecture|ja|長野県|12=draft}}, Japan. It was created in the early Edo period in [[1660]] (Manji 3). Owned by Shimosuwa Town, it has been designated a Municipal Cultural Property since [[1982]] (Shōwa 57) under the name "Manji no Sekibutsu (Mitarashi no Sekibutsu)."<ref name=town>[http://www.town.shimosuwa.lg.jp/www/contents/1001000000750/index.html Manji no Sekibutsu] - Shimosuwa Town, accessed February 11, 2021.</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.town.shimosuwa.lg.jp/www/contents/1496969553133/files/5-106.pdf |title=Municipal Cultural Property No. 34 |access-date=2023/8/20 |publisher=Shimosuwa Town}}</ref> It is situated across the {{ill|Togawa River|ja|砥川|12=draft}} from the {{ill|Suwa Taisha Shimosha Spring Shrine|ja|諏訪大社#下社|12=draft}}. The local area name "Sekibutsu" is derived from this statue.
The stone Buddha gained national recognition in the [[1970s]] when it was introduced by the artist {{ill|Taro Okamoto|ja|岡本太郎|12=draft}}.<ref name=kanko>[https://shimosuwaonsen.jp/万治の石仏/ Manji no Sekibutsu] - Shimosuwa Tourism Association, accessed February 11, 2021.</ref>
"Manji no Sekibutsu" is also a registered trademark owned by the Shimosuwa Chamber of Commerce.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=https://www.j-platpat.inpit.go.jp/c1800/TR/JP-1975-111530/F9955187CD2A8CF63F94F7E0BFD8C0A6B6A2FE9ED1871582677DE84CB61BA02A/40/ja |title=Trademark Registration No. 1326194 |access-date=2023/7/8 |publisher=National Center for Industrial Property Information and Training}}</ref>
== Overview == [[File:Manji-no sekibutsu (stone buddha) , 万治の石仏 - panoramio (20).jpg|thumb|Inscription "Namu Amida Butsu Manji 3rd Year, 11th Month, 1st Day, Ganshu Myōyo Jokō, Shinyo Hiroharu"]]
The stone Buddha measures 2.6 meters in height, 3.8 meters in width, and 3.7 meters in depth. It is made of andesite (hornblende-pyroxene andesite), with a Buddha head approximately 65 centimeters tall placed on a massive stone body.<ref name=kanko/><ref name=":4" /> The front of the body features a carved {{ill|Amida Nyorai|ja|阿弥陀如来|12=draft}} seated in {{ill|mudra|lt=Dhyanamudra|ja|印相#阿弥陀如来の印相|12=draft}}.<ref name=town/><ref name=":4" />
The robe is adorned with symbols such as {{ill|Swastika|ja|卍|12=draft}} (right-facing), the sun, thunder, clouds, rocks, and the moon, reflecting esoteric {{ill|Mikkyō|ja|密教|12=draft}} mandalas. These elements are attributed to the "One Body, Two Buddhas" doctrine of a sect of sculpting priests from the {{ill|Jōdo-shū|ja|浄土宗|12=draft}}, combining {{ill|Amida Nyorai|ja|阿弥陀如来|12=draft}} with {{ill|Vairocana|ja|大日如来|12=draft}}.<ref name=town/><ref name=":4" />
== Legend == A local legend recounts that during the construction of a large {{ill|torii|ja|鳥居|12=draft}} for Suwa Taisha in [[1657]] (Meireki 3), a stonecutter attempted to use the current stone Buddha as material. However, upon striking it with a chisel, the stone bled. Afraid of divine retribution, the construction ceased. The stone was later consecrated as an Amida Nyorai.<ref name=town/><ref name=kanko/>
== Gallery == <gallery> File:Manji-no-sekibutsu01n4592.jpg|Front view File:Manji-no-sekibutsu06n4592.jpg|Rear view File:Manji-no-sekibutsu05n4592.jpg|Face File:Manji-no-sekibutsu07s4592.jpg|Hand mudra </gallery>
== Access == * 16 minutes by bus from {{ill|Shimosuwa Station|ja|下諏訪駅|12=draft}} (Miyanoue bus stop) * {{ill|National Route 20 (Japan)|ja|国道20号|12=draft}}
