{{Infobox artwork | image_file = Yashiro, Shimosuwa, Suwa District, Nagano Prefecture 393-0000, Japan - panoramio.jpg | painting_alignment = right | image_size = 300px | title = Manji no Sekibutsu | caption = Front view | year = [[:en:1660|1660]] (Manji 3) | type = {{ill|Stone Buddha|ja|石仏|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Stone Buddha|qq=}} | material = [[:en:Andesite|Andesite]] (hornblende-pyroxene andesite) | height_metric = 2.6 | width_metric = 3.8 | metric_unit = m | accession = | city = [[:en:Shimosuwa|Shimosuwa, Nagano]], [[:en:Nagano Prefecture|Nagano Prefecture]] | museum = | website = {{URL|1=https://www.town.shimosuwa.lg.jp/www/contents/1001000000750/index.html|2=Manji no Sekibutsu (Shimosuwa Town)}} }}
'''Manji no Sekibutsu''' (万治の石仏) is a {{ill|Stone Buddha|lt=Stone Buddha|lt=Stone Buddha statue|ja|石仏|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/stone Buddha statue|qq=}} located in [[:en:Shimosuwa|Shimosuwa]], [[:en:Nagano Prefecture|Nagano Prefecture]], Japan. It was created in the early Edo period in [[:en:1660|1660]] (Manji 3). Owned by Shimosuwa Town, it has been designated a Municipal Cultural Property since [[1982]] (Shōwa 57) under the name "Manji no Sekibutsu (Mitarashi no Sekibutsu)."<ref name=town>[http://www.town.shimosuwa.lg.jp/www/contents/1001000000750/index.html Manji no Sekibutsu] - Shimosuwa Town, accessed February 11, 2021.</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.town.shimosuwa.lg.jp/www/contents/1496969553133/files/5-106.pdf |title=Municipal Cultural Property No. 34 |access-date=2023/8/20 |publisher=Shimosuwa Town}}</ref> It is situated across the {{ill|Togawa River|ja|砥川|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Togawa River|qq=}} from the {{ill|Suwa Taisha Shimosha Spring Shrine|ja|諏訪大社#下社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Suwa Taisha Shimosha Spring Shrine|qq=}}. The local area name "Sekibutsu" is derived from this statue.
The stone Buddha gained national recognition in the [[1970s]] when it was introduced by the artist [[:en:Tarō Okamoto|Taro Okamoto]].<ref name=kanko>[https://shimosuwaonsen.jp/万治の石仏/ Manji no Sekibutsu] - Shimosuwa Tourism Association, accessed February 11, 2021.</ref>
"Manji no Sekibutsu" is also a registered trademark owned by the Shimosuwa Chamber of Commerce.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=https://www.j-platpat.inpit.go.jp/c1800/TR/JP-1975-111530/F9955187CD2A8CF63F94F7E0BFD8C0A6B6A2FE9ED1871582677DE84CB61BA02A/40/ja |title=Trademark Registration No. 1326194 |access-date=2023/7/8 |publisher=National Center for Industrial Property Information and Training}}</ref>
== Overview == [[File:Manji-no sekibutsu (stone buddha) , 万治の石仏 - panoramio (20).jpg|thumb|Inscription "Namu Amida Butsu Manji 3rd Year, 11th Month, 1st Day, Ganshu Myōyo Jokō, Shinyo Hiroharu"]]
The stone Buddha measures 2.6 meters in height, 3.8 meters in width, and 3.7 meters in depth. It is made of andesite (hornblende-pyroxene andesite), with a Buddha head approximately 65 centimeters tall placed on a massive stone body.<ref name=kanko/><ref name=":4" /> The front of the body features a carved [[:en:Amitābha|Amida Nyorai]] seated in {{ill|mudra|lt=Dhyanamudra|ja|印相#阿弥陀如来の印相|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/mudra|qq=}}.<ref name=town/><ref name=":4" />
The robe is adorned with symbols such as [[:en:Swastika|Swastika]] (right-facing), the sun, thunder, clouds, rocks, and the moon, reflecting esoteric [[:en:Mikkyō|Mikkyō]] mandalas. These elements are attributed to the "One Body, Two Buddhas" doctrine of a sect of sculpting priests from the [[:en:Jōdo-shū|Jōdo-shū]], combining [[:en:Amitābha|Amida Nyorai]] with [[:en:Vairocana|Dainichi Nyorai]].<ref name=town/><ref name=":4" />
== Legend == A local legend recounts that during the construction of a large [[:en:Torii|torii]] for Suwa Taisha in [[:en:1657|1657]] (Meireki 3), a stonecutter attempted to use the current stone Buddha as material. However, upon striking it with a chisel, the stone bled. Afraid of divine retribution, the construction ceased. The stone was later consecrated as an Amida Nyorai.<ref name=town/><ref name=kanko/>
== Gallery == <gallery> File:Manji-no-sekibutsu01n4592.jpg|Front view File:Manji-no-sekibutsu06n4592.jpg|Rear view File:Manji-no-sekibutsu05n4592.jpg|Face File:Manji-no-sekibutsu07s4592.jpg|Hand mudra </gallery>
== Access == * 16 minutes by bus from [[:en:Shimo-Suwa Station|Shimosuwa Station]] (Miyanoue bus stop) * [[:en:Japan National Route 20|National Route 20 (Japan)]]
